Hurricane Rosa threatens Phoenix, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City with flash floods (drought areas may benefit)
It's rare for a tropical depression to reach Arizona, but that's what's likely to happen early next week when the remnants of Hurricane Rosa move across the deserted southwest, bringing with it the risk of tidal flooding.
The National Weather Service has already issued flash flood warnings for Monday and Tuesday from western Arizona to southern and eastern Nevada and southeastern California and Utah, including the cities of Phoenix, Flagstaff, Las Vegas and Salt Lake City.
Rosa is expected to approach with rain on Monday night and pass directly over Phoenix on Tuesday.
The National Weather Service in Phoenix tweeted that "Since 1950 only 10 tropical cyclones have come within 200 miles of Phoenix as a tropical storm or tropical depression!"
Katrina (1967) was within 40 miles of the Arizona border as a hurricane.
The latest models from the National Hurricane Center predict 5 to 10 inches of precipitation with occasional up to 15 inches in the Mogollon Rim of Arizona.
In other areas of the deserted southwest, including the central Rockies and the Great Basin, 2.5 to 5 centimeters are likely and occasionally up to 10 centimeters in total.
For those who are not at risk of flash flooding, the pink-colored rainfall associated with the drought in the region can be a boon.
Although flooding is a major concern, this rain is likely to be useful in part because of the current drought in the southwest.
According to the U.S. Drought Monitor, just over 40 percent of Arizona is experiencing at least extreme drought, the second highest category, weather.com reported.
First, the path of the hurricane means that Rosa will make landfall on the Baja California Peninsula in Mexico.
On Sunday morning, Rosa will remain hurricane-force with maximum winds of 86 miles per hour, and will be 400 miles south of Punta Eugenia, Mexico, before moving north at 12 miles per hour.
In the Pacific, the storm will hit colder waters and weaken.
So Rosa is expected to make landfall in Mexico Monday afternoon or evening with the force of a tropical storm.
The rainfall can be heavy in parts of Mexico, creating a significant risk of flooding.
From Baja California to the northwest of the Sonoran Desert, rainfall totals of two to six inches [7.5 to 15 cm] are expected, with up to eight inches [25 cm] possible, weather.com reported.
Rosa will then move northward over Mexico as a tropical storm, reach the Arizona border early Tuesday morning as a tropical depression, and then move up through Arizona into southern Utah by late Tuesday evening.
The main threat associated with Rosa or its remnants is very heavy rainfall in Baja California, the northwest Sonoran Desert, and the deserted southwest of the United States, the National Hurricane Center reported.
As a result of these rains, life-threatening floods and mudslides are expected in the desert and in mountainous areas.
