Macedonians vote in referendum on changing the country's name
The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether to change the country's name to the Republic of North Macedonia, a move that would settle a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked Macedonia's applications to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbor means that it claims Greek territory.
The two governments signed an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum, a boycott campaign that cast doubt on whether turnout would reach the 50 percent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was: Are you in favour of membership of NATO and the EU through the adoption of the agreement with Greece?
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia, membership in organizations like the EU and NATO is worth the price.
I have come today to vote for the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, as it means a safer life for all of us, said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although the result of the vote is not legally binding, enough Members of Parliament have said they will abide by the result to make it decisive.
The name change would require a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The state election commission said there were no reports of irregularities as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared with 34 percent in the last general election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their ballots.
"I am here to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko vote in a referendum on changing the country's name, which would pave the way for Macedonia to join NATO and the European Union, on September 30, 2018 in Strumica, Macedonia.
Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, set up a small stage outside the parliament in Skopje and set up chairs in front of tents set up by people who wanted to boycott the referendum.
We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads held high, not through the back door, Kavadarkov said.
We're a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to see us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of the integration between Europe and Asia.
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is more than 20 percent.
I believe that a large majority will be in favour, as more than 80 percent of our citizens are for the EU and NATO, Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a "yes" vote would be a "confirmation of our future".
According to a poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Research, between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, which is below the required turnout.
Another poll conducted by the Macedonian Telma TV found that 57 percent of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote "Yes".
For the referendum to be successful, the turnout must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failure of the referendum would be the first serious blow to the policy of the pro-Western government since it took power in May last year.
