John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizenship
Scotland's independent schools continue to excel academically, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding test scores, and is only underpinned by individual and joint successes in sport, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest possible standard of care for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought after as electives in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you've got their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current results of this year's examinations show that the languages with the highest pass rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages obtained A marks in their higher education exams.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored A's in the senior exams, while 72 percent of students learning German, 69 percent of students learning French, and 63 percent of students learning Spanish also scored A's.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an important skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered as electives, as well as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for problems filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future jobs.
As more and more open jobs require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the profession chosen, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future from such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilinguals an edge over competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was spoken as the only language by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
That's why it's important for today's children that we invest in language education now.
Children who speak several languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child's interests lie, independent schools will always have a range of languages to choose from with appropriately specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
At this time in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as international communication skills.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
It's the right thing to do.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
