While Ri reiterated North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization approach, where North Korea would be rewarded for taking successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim promised to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
The United States has also resisted calls for an easing of the severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The US insists on denuclearization first and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and is even against declaring the end of the war, Ri said.
The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a figment of the imagination of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions are deepening our distrust.
Ri did not comment on plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: If South Korea, instead of the US, had been the other party to the denuclearisation issue, the denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to this standstill.
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was vastly different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missiles were inevitably going to hit the US mainland after "evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: Whether it takes two years, three years or five months  doesn't matter.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
