The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and he believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
And then one girl came up to me and said, "Why don't I just learn about this now, in my last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was.
The course, which was held for the first time this year, explained to students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to launch the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see a picture of a dorm room and click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books, which provide information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, and cancer.
Then, a map of the university grounds with interactive symbols is used to encourage them to reflect on their daily routine.
