National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research is being carried out at a farm in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape for food.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insight into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track dwarf and mosquito bats, as well as brown long-eared and water bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recorders are placed at key locations on the property to record the activity of the bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with portable detectors.
An expert analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bat calls and determine which species is doing what.
A map and habitat report are then drawn up to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help to identify the benefits of habitat management measures such as grassland and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat stocks in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which affects sleeping places and leads to habitat loss.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their night-hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-tracking to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for over 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the bat issue very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly conduct examinations, inspections of sleeping areas and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Property manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
Here in Threave, we have a great bat area, he explains.
