Here are some key facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was just celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a government district that stretches along a coastal strip of over 300 km (180 mi) in the northwest of Sulawesi island.
The government district, an administrative unit under the province, had an estimated 299,200 inhabitants in 2017.
The fishing and agriculture sectors are the main sources of income for the economy of Central Sulawesi, particularly the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to Indonesia's Disaster Management Agency, Palu and Donggala have been hit by earthquakes and tsunamis several times in the past 100 years.
In 1938, over 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West Donggala was hit by a tsunami in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A powerful earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami on December 26, affecting 14 countries and killing 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, nearly half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra between late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias Islands off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake shook southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, and triggered a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake hits the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
Over 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake shook one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A small earthquake shook the Pidie Jaya government district in Aceh, causing destruction and panic as people remembered the devastation of the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time no tsunami was caused, but over 100 people died when buildings collapsed.
2018: A major earthquake hit the popular tourist island of Lombok, Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, mostly in the northern part of the island.
